Core Infrastructure (not user-facing sections, but affects everything)
app.py — Main Entry Point & Navigation Shell
Score: 82/100 | Grade: B+
Strengths:
•	Lazy-loading sections via importlib — only the active section pays import cost
•	Role-based visibility with clean fallback
•	Section transition state prevents stale renders
•	Global filter signature detection auto-clears relevant cache
•	Connection probing with graceful degraded-mode rendering
Weaknesses:
•	700+ lines in a single file; sidebar logic, header rendering, bookmark panel, and Ask OVERWATCH all co-located
•	unsafe_allow_html=True used 6+ times — works because of html.escape() but is fragile at scale
•	st.cache_data.clear() is a global nuke in SiS deployments
•	Module version checks with importlib.reload() scattered throughout — feels like a hot-patch workaround
Recommendations:
1.	Extract sidebar into utils/sidebar.py
2.	Extract header rendering into utils/chrome.py
3.	Replace st.cache_data.clear() with per-section salt invalidation
4.	Replace inline HTML with Streamlit components where possible to reduce XSS surface
________________________________________
utils/query.py — Tiered Query Runner
Score: 91/100 | Grade: A-
Strengths:
•	Four-tier caching (live 30s, recent 300s, historical 1800s, metadata 4h) — mature design
•	Per-query telemetry with budget pressure warnings
•	Result-size guards with admin vs standard thresholds
•	De-duplicated warning messages
•	safe_sql(), safe_identifier(), sql_literal() cover input sanitization
Weaknesses:
•	Result guard runs AFTER to_pandas() — Snowflake credits already burned
•	_cache_context() includes exceptions_only_mode which busts cache unnecessarily
•	No SQL-level LIMIT injection before execution
•	safe_identifier() allows $ character
Recommendations:
1.	Add a _inject_limit() pre-pass for non-admin queries
2.	Remove exceptions_only_mode from cache key — filter client-side
3.	Add a max_rows parameter to run_query() that appends LIMIT before execution
________________________________________
utils/session.py — Session Management
Score: 88/100 | Grade: B+
Strengths:
•	55-minute TTL with health check before reconnect
•	Query tag applied at session level for cost attribution
•	Statement timeout (840s) prevents runaway queries
•	Dual-path connection (SiS injected vs Streamlit secrets)
Weaknesses:
•	3 sequential ALTER SESSION SET statements on cold start (could be batched)
•	SELECT 1 keepalive every 55 minutes — low cost but unnecessary if session object tracks state
•	No connection retry with backoff
Recommendations:
1.	Batch ALTER SESSION statements: ALTER SESSION SET QUERY_TAG='OVERWATCH', STATEMENT_TIMEOUT_IN_SECONDS=840, TIMEZONE='UTC'
2.	Add exponential backoff on reconnection failure
3.	Consider checking session._conn.is_closed() before SELECT 1
________________________________________
utils/admin.py — Admin Guardrails & Audit
Score: 90/100 | Grade: A-
Strengths:
•	Admin toggle with role-based defaults (ACCOUNTADMIN/SYSADMIN default on)
•	Date range clamping (35 days standard, 90 days admin)
•	Full audit trail with SQL hash, execution context, and confirmation text
•	require_admin_enabled() gate before any destructive action
Weaknesses:
•	Audit INSERT runs on same warehouse as dashboard reads — could compete under load
•	_current_execution_context() executes SELECT CURRENT_USER(), CURRENT_ROLE() per audit write — could cache
Recommendations:
1.	Cache execution context for the session lifetime (role/user don't change mid-session)
2.	Consider async audit writes or a separate XS warehouse for audit INSERTs
